                    Nervous tissue allows for incredibly rapid responses, but it has limitations. Firstly, electrical impulses only reach cells that are directly connected by nerve fibers. Secondly, once an impulse is sent, a neuron takes time to reset its mechanism before it can fire again. To provide a steady, slow, and wide-reaching coordination across the entire body (like regulating growth or puberty), we rely on the <strong>Endocrine System</strong>. This system uses chemical messengers called hormones, which are secreted directly into the bloodstream to reach every single cell.
