                <h2>Introduction to Reproduction</h2>
                <div class="reading-pane">
                    <strong>The Energy Cost of Reproduction</strong><br>
                    Unlike essential life processes such as respiration or digestion, reproduction is not strictly necessary to keep an individual organism alive. In fact, creating a new individual takes a massive amount of energy. So, why do organisms waste this energy? The answer lies in the survival of the species, not the individual. Reproduction is the only biological mechanism that ensures a species does not go extinct, allowing their unique DNA blueprint to be passed forward through time.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- LECTURE READING 5 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>DNA Copying & Variation</h2>
                <div class="reading-pane">
                    <strong>The Spice of Survival</strong><br>
                    The fundamental event in reproduction is the creation of a DNA copy inside the cell nucleus. However, no biochemical reaction is absolutely reliable. Therefore, the DNA copies generated will be similar, but rarely identical to the original. These minor copying errors create <strong>Variation</strong>. While severe errors can cause a cell to die, slight variations are the "spice of life." They allow a species to slowly adapt to environmental changes (like rising temperatures or new diseases), ensuring their long-term survival.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

